review_title:
5.0 out of 5 stars
Surprisingly good travel headphones for the price.
review_text: This is a Boomer review since younger people know much more about headphones than I do, and everyone has them.  But for those who only use headphones on the plane, especially for the noise canceling feature, this is for you.  I specifically looked for plug-in headphones because they are more comfortable than earbuds, and more reliable than bluetooth.  No, these are not Bose headphones, but hilariously, they rank second to Bose on many reviewers' lists!I bought these to replace my 15 year old Audio Technica headphones that still work but are falling apart.  I took both pairs with me on a recent trip and did a comparison.  I could not tell a difference between them, even though the Audio Technica ones covered my ears better.  When not watching movies I wore them just for the noise-cancelling feature, which worked just fine.  I am a relatively small woman so larger people might have a different experience with ear coverage.  These earphones fold up and become quite compact so they don't take up much room in your carry-on bag.  They fit neatly into small, semi-circular cases that are readily available on Amazon, and which  I highly recommend.  The nearly identical version of these headphones at about half the price does not have the noise canceling feature.  Make sure you get the ones with a product number that ends in NC.

review_text: My sister got these for me for Christmas, knowing that i was looking for noise cancelling headphones so I wasnâ€™t destroying my hearing. Thatâ€™s not true at all. I have to turn them up just as loud as my $10 wireless earbuds. The sound quality is okay but it removes maybe about 50% of ambient noise. Also, the sound quality is only good when turned up. These get quite dull and somewhat muddy at low volume which again makes them basically useless as advertised. Theyâ€™re just cheap over ear headphones. Thatâ€™s it. Iâ€™d be fine with them if they werenâ€™t trying to claim 95% noise cancellation. Find something else. You also have to use a battery which is fun, I love listening to music only for the battery to die halfway through. Theyâ€™re not rechargeable batteries either, itâ€™s a physical battery. review_title:
5.0 out of 5 stars
Comfortable, quality sound, great bluetooth
review_text: I bought the h10 (holiday sale $22) to use with a 9 band equalizer. I'm not yet willing or ready for hearing aids! I used an optical splitter (BlueRigger Toslink digital optical audio splitter adapter around $8). Connect splitter to TV optical output and one port goes to soundbar and other port to the digital to analog decoder which ill describe  in a minute. I can now hear 2KHz and above thx to the equalizer (behringer mini fbq800 from Sweetwater.com around $70). BTW, I have Bose OVER the ear ANC ($$$$) but wanted simple ON the ears and h10 is perfect ($). My wife likes the sound very low from the soundbar and I can now turn up the headphones volume to add many more years to a happy marriage. As for gear, connect TV optical to OREI DA34 digital to analog decoder audio converter (this unit processes the all-important Dolby signal and PCM) around $30. Connect the DA34 to the equalizer. In order to provide Bluetooth, output the equalizer to a wireless Bluetooth transmitter. I use the MEE audio Connect around $20. Turn on TV, equalizer, put h10 into pairing mode (press button for 5 sec) and press MEE button. Voila. Yes, there is a very slight audio latency with Bluetooth in the headphones, but the soundbar volume is low and the earphones is a bit higher so it is not distracting for me. If the soundbar is off, it's all moot.

category_path: Electronics > â€º > Headphones, Earbuds & Accessories > â€º > Headphones & Earbuds > â€º > Over-Ear Headphones
review_title:
5.0 out of 5 stars
Done With Buds Forever, Incredible Value
review_text: I collect headphones, or as some might say, I'm a headphone hobbyist. In my collection are HiFiMan, Sennheiser, and AKG high-end headphones. I always used a set of buds for knocking around, walking the dog, and talking on the phone. My last two pairs were from Soundcore, including Liberty Pro 3s which I paid over $100 for. They were okay, but despite trying many different tips, they would fall out of my ear, not provide a good seal, I'd accidentally hang-up on folks by pushing a bud back into my ear or eventually get clogged with earwax.This time when it came time to replace my buds I thought I'd try something different. Despite my bad experiences with buds, I've always appreciated the value, sound, and features of Soundcore products. Because I have no use for gimmicks like noise-canceling, etc., I looked through the line-up to see which set of Soundcore cans had none of those useless (to me) features and found these for $25-ish.As far as price-to-quality ratio, these are easily the best headphones I've ever owned. The microphone is stellar (it sounds as good as most podcasts I listen to, even better than some), the sound for listening to calls or podcasts is great, and to my surprise, music sounds better than virtually any bud I've ever owned. And even music sounds great, which was not even my main usage for these. Do they have as flat and detailed of a response as my best, open-back headphones...? Of course not. They have a bit of boost in the bass, like many less expensive earphones. However, even this can be adjusted with the EQ in the free SoundCore app.Much to my surprise, given that they don't even cover the entire ear, wearing them even without anything playing seems to block out about 85% of outside noise. I will say, they fit very snugly, some might even say tight. My head must be on the smaller side, because I rarely have to extend headphones beyond the smallest size, and still they are VERY snug. I doesn't bother me, but they might become uncomfortable after an hour or two. However, I don't use these for long listening sessions... I have many, much better wired headphones for that.These are the best Bluetooth headphones I've ever had, including my first pair ever, my now long-gone $300 Sony MDR-1R. For $25! For that money, I was expecting something with good utility for my purposes. What I got was a really fun pair of cans.

review_text: Anker always comes through with excellent products that hit the sweet spot on price without compromises in features. The H30i has an awesome battery life that's taken me multiple days to totally run through. The microphone quality is great for phone calls and I never have issues with clarity. Audio quality is great, bass is great. The buttons are just what you need and nothing unnecessary yet give a satisfying and responsive click. The H30i's USB-C port is great and let's you get rid of your outdated USB Micro-B cables. The earcups have the ability to swivel and spin together with an adjustable band for improved comfort. The design is professional yet elegant. The H30i even supports a headphone jack. Unfortunately, the H30i's internal microphone does not work while wired, but you can buy an aux cable with an inline microphone to use the H30i as a proper headset even while wired. Absolutely get this if you're looking for full-sized headphones, don't want to break the bank and not concerned about active noise cancellation.

review_title:
4.0 out of 5 stars
Obnoxious Interference
review_text: Usually, I prefer to use wireless ear buds, but I use them for hours a day and was getting frustrated when needing to take them out to charge. As an alternative, I looked at over the ear wired headphones that connected with a c-type USB, but I definitely didn't want to spend more than $30 on a pair since they'd be my in-between while my buds charge, so here we are with the Kensington headphones. Overall, they are very good - sound quality is great, and despite the ear coverage not being a tight seal, enough ambient noise is blocked so that I can enjoy the music, but not so blocked that I can't hear important background noises (doorbell, kids screaming, etc.). They are comfortable on my ears and on my head, which hasn't been my experience in the pas with headphones. That said, there is random and often obnoxious interference that comes through, and I can't pinpoint if maybe it's something with my phone or some kind of external interference from a computer or something like that, but it does seem that no matter where I set my phone, the interference happens. If you've ever used dial-up internet, you will remember the unique tapping that would emit through computer speakers just before the phone rang, and that is not only the type of interference, but has many times been the exact sound I get. All-in-all, even with that interference, these are good headphones.

review_text: I usually don't write reviews. When I do, it's because a product actually solves my problem.You see, almost all the headset you find on Amazon all comes with a few buttons, and "long press here to turn on" and "push that button to pause/play" that kind of stuff. All that does is to confuse the consumer. I need to buy a headset for a senior family member, I cannot teach them to do "long press" here and "pause/play" there. I need a headset that behaves like an old school headset: just plug it in and it works!This headset does JUST THAT! No buttons, no manual to read, just plug into your phone and it works!If you get frustrated by electronics designed by engineers who don't understand consumers, buy this headset!

review_title:
3.0 out of 5 stars
Not suitable for my needs as a constant user.
review_text: Iâ€™m a nearly 24/7 headphones wearer so have a lot of important criteria. My current daily drivers are the skullcandy uproar wireless, which have been frustratingly discontinued, soâ€¦ the search begins. First and foremost, my headphones need to be comfortable and they can not make me overheat. These were both a little uncomfortable, and already made me feel too warm within just a few minutes of wear. I specifically gave these a chance because another reviewer said they didnâ€™t cause overheating, but this was not the case for me. A lot of the discomfort was from the tightness of the band, which will loosen over time so Iâ€™m willing to forgive it, but the ear cupsâ€”while decently soft and squishyâ€”seemed to reflect my own body heat back at me and amplify it. This would make them unwearable for even an hour, let alone a full day. I will say that I appreciated the design of how the band is adjusted, because they adjust higher up, meaning it gives both a little more width and a little more length than other, similar designs. Many headphones continue to squeeze your ears tight to the side of your face no matter how long the extension is, but the additional widening helped enough that I can see how theyâ€™d be very comfortable with some wearing in.These sound excellent, which Iâ€™ve come to expect from Skullcandy. The sound is clear and un-muffled, and does not feel lacking. I donâ€™t really know the differences in sound descriptions and words, but skullcandy has always sounded very, very good to me when it comes to listening to every kind of media I can think of.The buttons are too small to quickly find when you need to pause or adjust the volume, and I pause my sound a significantly high number of times per day, so this would be a problem. I could add dots of puffy paint to them if I wanted to make them more prominent, but Iâ€™d already decided these werenâ€™t keepers. Theyâ€™re also grouped really closely together and feel sort of â€œmushyâ€ when you press them, which makes the physical act of doing so a bit difficult if your fingertips are hyperflexible. The absolute distaste I have for these buttons was a HUGE part of rejecting the headphones overall, as well as the fact there seems to be a bit of a delay when you press play/pause to when it actually activates. So on top of pressing the button being a slow event, the action itself is slowed, as well. No thanks.All in all, these are not the WORST headphones Iâ€™ve ever tried, but I decided in less than an hour they werenâ€™t worth a hoot at all for me.If youâ€™re also a nonstop headphones user, Iâ€™d recommend finding something else for your daily driver.

category_path: Electronics > â€º > Headphones, Earbuds & Accessories > â€º > Headphones & Earbuds > â€º > On-Ear Headphones
review_title:
5.0 out of 5 stars
Great for bass lovers
review_text: I always appreciate the fidelity of decent wired headphones over those with Bluetooth connections. These didn't disappoint, with a few qualifications.I compared them to a few other major brand on-ear wired headphones and these definitely had the best bass response and a good clean sound.Bass was strong and clean, definitely the main feature of these headphones, and a great reason to get them if you like powerful bass. But in all three EQ settings I found the mids and treble to be a bit weak compared to the other headphones I compared these to. Although weak in my opinion, the sound across all frequency ranges was very clean... much better than lower quality headphones.The microphone placement on the control module allows for good clean voice pickup (better than microphones located on headphone cups or earbuds). It does a good job masking the sound of the cable rubbing on your shirt (which some others don't).They don't come with any documentation, so here are a few tips. To toggle the EQ among bass-favoring, voice-favoring, or default, you need to hold down the volume ( + and - ) buttons simultaneously for 2 seconds. The setting will be announced as it switches. Tap the center button to pause/play, hold it briefly to activate voice commands (like Siri).These headphones fold flat for storage and the headband is adjustable, but they lack horizontal pivots on the earcups, so depending on your head shape they may press harder on the bottoms or tops of your ears. I didn't find this to be a big deal and they were comfortable enough on my big head.Overall, these are great sounding for the price, and if you're a bass lover you'll really enjoy them.

category_path: Electronics > â€º > Headphones, Earbuds & Accessories > â€º > Headphones & Earbuds > â€º > Over-Ear Headphones
review_title:
5.0 out of 5 stars
Shouldn't sound or feel this good for $13 ( PortaPro alternative )
review_text: I bought these along with the somewhat coveted JLabs Rewind ( gen 2 ) Bluetooth headphones. I bought both because I've been looking for something that won't cause me physical ear fatigue or hurt immediately upon wearing.I REALLY wanted to love the JLabs because they offer something that the JVC Flats cannot.... No wires.  I LOATHE wires.That said. I will take the cables on these JVC Flats ANY day of the week because of what they offer over the JLabs Rewind.  Before I state what that is exactly, let me just say that the JLabs are about as comfortable as the JVC Flats.  Maybe more... But not quite,  without modifications.  I'll explain, because it's relevant.I have small ears.  And small ear canals. This is why I can't wear in-ear buds for too long, and is also why certain headphones hurt my ears or skull, depending upon how where and how they sit on my head and ears. It's a freaking curse.I started looking for headphones where one of the main selling points is being lightweight and comfortable.  Both these JVC'S and JLabs seemed to fit the bill when looking at their descriptions and reviews.  So, I bought both.I went into buying the JVC Flats knowing there was no mic or volume control, which I am actually fine with.  So I won't ding ding a star for it.What I wasn't expecting from the JVC Flats though.... Was how freaking good the sound quality would be! I have had several pairs of JVC marshmallow in ears, and now that I think about it, those sounded great, and are like fifteen bucks, so... Maybe I shouldn't be surprised?I should not that I also primarily wanted these for podcasts.  But when I heard the JVC Flats, I put on some music and was kind of floored.They instantly reminded me of Koss PortaPros, but with a tad more forward low and mid bass, maybe?  I used the PortaPros A LOT in my 20s and 30s and am now 53, so I've lost frequency range throughout the years.And they're LOUD! I don't need them to be this loud, but this is a terrible issue with the JLabs Rewind.  They're incredibly low.  Maybe lower voltage to increase battery life, but it's horrible.I'd have to put the volume to about 85% on the JLabs for basic, comfortable listening levels, whereas with these JVC'S, it's about 40% or less.  Fantastic.  And again, loud means nothing if it's loud and garbage.  These are loud and clear with no real bass mushiness even at uncomfortably loud levels.  Crystal clear.  Awesome.They fit snug on my ears, and the ear pads are cushy and fairly soft.  The outer layer is that faux leather material that always seems to eventually tear on headphones, so we'll see on that one....My only wish is that the actual driver housing was a TAD wider because while the driver seems to be positioned perfectly against my ear canal, the housing edges kind of hit the edges of my ear, causing some minor discomfort.Someone with normal, non-freakishly small ears, (which is most people), won't be bothered by this I guess.  What else. The head band, even though it has no padding, is barely noticeable.  Likely due to how light the frame is.  The band adjustment gives you a really pleasing tactile single groove click when adjusting.  Nice touch.I might give the JLabs a slight win in comfort, but ONLY if changing the foam pads on them, to something more foamy/cushy and soft.  As they are, the JLabs driver housing is very rigid and  my ears really feel that.  If I kept them, I'd modify them with some extra foam.  Otherwise, they're lighter than the JVC 's with a smaller earpiece frame.I might actually try to modify these JVC ear ups to make them wider.  I'll likely also buy a few spare sets because this pair is a gem.Great job JVC.If there's one negative thing I can say about them, it's that they're not being made with USB-C instead of just the 3.5mm input plug.  I hate having to use dongles. review_text: I recently bought my second pair of these HA-S160 headphones, to replace my previous pair.  For sound and comfort, I've been completely happy with them.  I use them when seated at my PC, to listen to music and watch videos, for moderate stretches of time (never really lengthy).  My only complaint is a material issue --- the outermost part of the foam earpads are covered with an extremely thin plastic/rubber-like membrane, and over time the membrane has come apart and is falling/peeling away from the foam.  This is the sole reason I decided to replace my old pair with a new pair.  My old pair is several years old, however, so it took a while for the material to deteriorate.  Despite this issue, and considering how happy I've been with them otherwise, plus the fact that the price is quite affordable, I recommend these headphones as a good product.

review_text: While I've been a loyal customer to Philips for a long time and usually satisfied, this time they've let me down. Sound quality is a steep downgrade from comparably priced headsets to such a degree that they fall into a lower tier entirely. Connectivity is unreliable and often requires multiple disconnects and reconnects just to work properly. Headphones will say "device connected" without actually being so. Worst of the lot though is the battery life. With a prior, similarly-priced headset I was able to go up to a week on a charge while this one can't get through the day. The battery life is only functionally 75% of the listed capacity, as every 90 seconds the headphones will interrupt your audio to repeat a "BATTERY LOW" voice warning. There is no way to turn this off and it will interrupt a single song two to three times, while the meter will show you having up to a quarter of your battery life left. The device can still be in the green on a battery meter and still will not function without being charged, in the most infuriating way imaginable. Budgeting in an extra $20 and going for a different brand will pay off to spare the frustration alone.

review_title:
2.0 out of 5 stars
Another example of a company ruining a product with absurd automatic functions
review_text: I bought these to replace a pair of BT510 that broke in my carry-on during a flight a few weeks ago. These were in sale, so figured I'd try the better model. I can't stand them. I think they sound a little worse than the cheaper 210s, but this is another product completely ruined by trying to decide for you what you want to do, and doing it, whether it's okay with you or not. They have some absurd feature where they automatically send a mute / pause command to any connected device if you so much as slightly light one side off your ear. Well first off that's just annoying in the first place, but even if I was into that kind of thing, they're so over-sensitive, that I've been using them for about a full week now, and not a single day has gone by that they havent shut off my music from me taking a sip of a drink, talking, or even just sitting absolutely still. SO frustrating. I'm going to buy another set of 210s because no way these are working on a flight with my head touching a headrest. To make matters worse, the first time I paired them to my phone, the driver asked permissions to link to my Google account?!?!? WHY?!?! I said no, and it did it anyway. Ita none of Googles business what headphones I'm wearing, and my email address and phone info darn sure isnt any of JBLs business. Only giving them 2 stars because the sound quality is half way decent when they dont stop your music. Oh, and the icing on the cake is the mute button functions as a hang up button on Teams, so yah, these hung up on a work conference call because I moved my mouth, and they sensed movement on my head and decided that means I want to hang up. Don't recommend these for any use, because they do what they want, and providing bare minimum basic function a set of speakers attached to your ears, is not one of those things! They're also extremely uncomfortable on my head compared to the 510s that are less than half the price.

review_title:

SENSORY RELIEF
review_text: I have not used noise cancelling headphones before but after my confirmed Autism diagnosis I have realized much of what I thought was anxiety is actually sensory overwhelm. I decided to try these first to see if headphones are something that will help me before spending over $150 for the more recommended pairs.Upon just placing them on your head (not turning on) the sounds around me are already muffled. The moment I turned them on it was further improved and the holy-amazing-batman sound cancellation was clear the moment the noise cancelling turned on. Then when connected to my phone to play lofi music is the next best thing to being in a quiet room by myself. I have been wearing them for about twenty minutes and I already feel so relaxed whereas my child and mother are talking on the sofa next to me and only hear a light sound every couple minutes compared to the constant talking I would be hearing without that would slowly drive me to full blow irritation and aggravation. They have not started to bother my ears yet or give me a headache. Time will tell how they hold up and how long I can use them before getting uncomfortable.

category_path: Electronics > â€º > Headphones, Earbuds & Accessories > â€º > Headphones & Earbuds > â€º > Over-Ear Headphones
review_title:
4.0 out of 5 stars
Good value solid BT headphones, middling ANC
review_text: Viewed strictly as BT headphones, the JBUDS LUX are pretty decent.  I find the sound quite good for movies and fine for casual music listening.  The ANC and pass-through features are of some use, and the headphones are comfortable enough for, e.g., watching a movie, though the earcups don't "breathe" very well (I notice some reviewers refer to them as "sweaty", which is fair enough), so you'll probably want to take some breaks between calls (it makes a surprisingly good phone headset) or if listening to music for an extended period.  If you're interested in knowing more, details follow.USE CASE (you can skip this if not interested):Just to provide context, I'll mention I bought these at an attractive price for dedicated use with my living room TV, which supports Bluetooth but puts the pairing/unpairing bits behind such cumbersome menus, and behaves so badly with dual-connect BT devices (forcing you to completely reset BT volume, etc., when the headphone's interrupted by another device), that I prefer to just keep a pair of headphones paired exclusively to that TV.  Since I normally listen through a home theater sound system, I prefer to use more value-priced headphones for such occasional private-listening use.SOUND QUALITY:It's what headphones are for, and the JBUDS LUX does the basics competently.  They're replacing my old blue JBL E55BT phones (which were getting a bit the worse for wear, various bits of plastic trim breaking and the earcup cushions falling apart), and get pretty close to those in sound quality, the JBL being a bit "brighter", the JLAB's high end a bit more subdued, for what that's worth (no EQ tuning with the app for this comparison since I'm pairing them directly with a TV); as TV headphones they're kinda great.  I'm no audio  critic, but I've watched some music videos with them and there's nothing distracting about their performance, which is more than I can say for some other bargain headphones I've tried.  Switching to them directly from my Bose one can notice less distinct highs and less overall "warmth" to the sound, but heard on their own they're perfectly fine.ANC FEATURES:Overall noise-canceling performance is a bit unusual.  First off, hats off to JLAB for having an actual OFF option in the ANC control cycle, not just an ANC/aware toggle.  In cases where neither ANC nor pass-through is needed, turning those off maximizes the already long battery life, a welcome option.  Passive sound isolation is pretty good, so I usually have the ANC turned off.As for the ANC itself, my experience has differed from reviewers that claim turning on the ANC does less than the headphones' passive sound isolation, in that my own casual testing showed significant noise reduction.  It probably depends on what sounds you're trying to cancel - it works best at reducing the volume of continuous background noise like fans, road noise, etc., not so much for more transient sounds.  So it's somewhat effective and not very sophisticated, and that's about what I'd expect for this price point.  I won't be taking them on an airplane (where my Bose QC 45s do really well), so we'd need feedback from someone who's tried that for more of a torture test.The headphones' "aware" mode is a different matter, and unlike what I've experienced on other headphones offering a pass-through feature.  It's quite functional, but somewhat low fidelity.  While it's easy to hear your surroundings in this mode, sound quality is somewhat boxy/tinny, a bit better than an old landline phone (should you be old enough to recall ever hearing such a thing).  The Bose headphones mentioned above are my daily drivers for music and podcasts, and by comparison has such natural sounding pass-through I sometimes forget I have them on.  That's not something that would happen with the JBUDS LUX.MICROPHONE:Especially in light of the so-so pass-through sound quality, one surprising feature that bears mention is the microphone quality on phone calls or meetings.  Folks on the other end of the line tell me the sound matches or surpasses that of my old Sennheiser and current Bose headphones.  I tend to prefer boom mics, but apparently what's built into these earcups is better than I'd have expected, so on top of everything else it would be a good phone headset.COMFORT AND BUILD QUALITY:These are quite comfortable for value headphones.  Both the earcups and headband are well-padded, and the adjustment mechanism feels solid, with satisfying detents to make it easy to return to your preferred setting after, e.g.,  collapsing for storage.  The controls are also satisfying to use, with enough tactile feedback to ease operating by touch alone (more on this below).The earcup pads are covered with a soft vinyl-type material while the part of the headband sitting atop your head is fabric-covered.  Adjustment I think fabric earcup pads would have improved comfort, since the material covering the stock pads doesn't really breathe too well, though this would likely compromise the sound isolation a bit.  Going back to the Bose QC 45 as reference, its protein leather earcup pads breathe well enough that I've worn them on multi-hour plane flights without my ears getting uncomfortably warm.  You'll want to take occasional breaks from the JBUDS LUX.CONTROLS:The controls are easy to operate and do the job quite well.  The three control surfaces are:- a round button on top to cycle through ANC settings (ANC, aware/passthrough, off)- a rocker/toggle in the middle to handle volume (just click once in either direction to go up or down), track skip (push and hold to jump forward or back, though as with any such control the exact behavior will depend on the specific device or application), or cycling through EQ presets (press both sides of the toggle at once).- a round button at the bottom that handles power, BT pairing, call answer, and even summoning your Google/Siri assistant.  I got used to these quite quickly even with limited use.Like a lot of modern BT devices, the JBUDS LUX provides voice prompts for certain events like startup, shutdown, etc.  The voice is clear and easily understood, though I'd note the mild disappointment in its tone when saying  "JLAB off" is mildly amusing.One small thing worth mentioning is that the headphones not only report their level of charge to your paired device (if, e.g., your phone shows you this), but also announce the state of charge during power-up.  That voice info is really useful in my case, since the TV I'm using doesn't report battery level for connected BT devices.  I make special mention of this because the EB55BT, like some other JBL speakers and headphones I've owned, never reports battery level at all, just produces an annoying beep when the battery is "low" (whatever that is) that gets more frequent until you charge it back up (or the headphones just stop, I guess).VALUE/RATING:Something to consider in assessing the value of these is the price.  I got them on Prime Days for less than $50, but they're currently closer to $80, which is getting close to the "on sale" price of some better hardware.  That said, the price on the JBUDS LUX swings about quite a bit, so maybe put it in your shopping list and keep an eye out for buying opportunities.  For $50 this is a 5-star value, but the listed "full" price knocks this down to a four-star.

These are great headphones for what I wanted/needed them for
review_text: I purchased these ANC wireless over ear headphones shortly before the Fourth of July because of a condition that causes me to be easily startled by unexpected sounds or loud noises. While I don't expect any noise-cancelling headphones to completely block these, and in fact I did hear neighborhood fireworks when they were set off, these headphones eliminated enough of the noise when ANC was turned on, that I was able to be present at a family celebration on the Fourth of July, and still function. Sure, I was listening to music playing on my phone most of the time, but at least I was able to show my face. As for the quality and other characteristics of these headphones, when properly adjusted and positioned, they are comfortable to wear. I am no acoustic engineer, but to me these seem to have decent sound, for what I listen to, and they were more affordable than some comparable headphones from brands that in my opinion, part of what you are paying for might be the brand itself (and status and bragging rights, but I will do me and you do you). I will admit that I haven't used these enough since I bought them, to give you my opinion on their long-term performance in the area of battery life and charging times, but so far, I cannot complain. Both of these appear to be holding up to the manufacturer's claims. All things considered, I am happy with my purchase and plan to keep these.
